array('Type'=>'Incarna','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Character or Descendant Incarna. Often the easiest Embodiment to create Fantastical Characters, but not often suitable to all Genres and Conflicts.'),
array('Type'=>'Personality','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Character Personality. Often the most satisfying embodiment, but can lead to easy identification, and unsubtle Plots.'),
array('Type'=>'Core','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Character Core. This can create very satisfying embodiments that can be suitable for most Genres.'),
array('Type'=>'Handicap','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Character Handicap. This can create quite secretive and subtle embodiments that can be very difficult to spot, sometimes. Other times Handicap Embodiments can be very obvious, and in the case of Woes, glaring.'),
array('Type'=>'Monster','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Character Monster Facet.This Monster might be a Dragon, an Orc Horde, or just a human Villain. Monsters can be great fun, but are rarely subtle, where possible when using Monster embodiments the Plot Demon may want to keep the exact nature of the Monster a secret for as long as it can.'),
array('Type'=>'Proficiency','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a single Proficiency from that Facet. Characters or Descendants that have the Proficiency may be Hooked.'),
array('Type'=>'Annex','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet within an Annex, this could be a Subtle Nimbed, or be as obvious as being Root, Channel and at least one Umbral. The Annex may be within Descendants, or Characters.'),
array('Type'=>'Tone','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as the Tone of the Scene, Act or Story. This can be an easy way to embody some Facets, but can be restrictive and may not suit your style. Use with care.'),
array('Type'=>'Ordeal','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as an Ordeal (or Test). Simple and effective, but can be obvious and boring if used too often. A good embodiment during a Warp Fray, not very good across a whole Story.'),
array('Type'=>'Location','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Location. this can be a very subtle embodiment, while still allowing the Conflict to progress. There can be a danger of overusing the same Location as the Embodiment is such a satisfying one. But any Location where the action returns again and again is probably an embodiment of something from one of the higher Conflicts, anyway.'),
array('Type'=>'Obstacle','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as an Obstacle that the player must overcome. The Obstacle should match Suit with the Facet (Obstacles are defined by Cards normally). Obstacle embodiments can be the most subtle, you need not reuse the same Obstacle over and over, and they allow for Red Herring Facets from the same Suit to be misdirected easily.'),
array('Type'=>'Descendant','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Descendant Incarna. In the case of a Yonder Conflict this may result in a Location anyway. Conflicts embodied with Descendants can be very subtle. Commonly used by Invention Plots.'),
array('Type'=>'Pact-Descendant','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Pact Descendant or group of Characters such as the Party or a Guild. This Embodiment is the most obvious to use when you are starting out. The Players become one side of the Conflict fighting the other side. It is also great for modelling any number of political and social situations.'),
array('Type'=>'Quest','Description'=>'The Conflict Embodies one Facet as a Quest that the Character must attempt. This can be great for creating Chapters of Epics and is an obvious way of deciding NPC Ends, but be wary of using Quests in a substitute for any other Character development. Great fun, but best used sparingly.'),
array('Type'=>'Lore','Description'=>'The Conflict embodies as a special type of Annex/ Descendant/ Extra Character called a Lore. Lores are the rumours the Players hear about the enemy and themselves as the story goes on. Lores might grant extra abilities and skills to any Character as it is revealed that they are a powerful wizard, a Necromancer, with a skeleton horde, armed with magickal longsword, etc.')		
